  <abstract displayLabel="Description">Butler describes her early years in St. Francisville, the religious experience that prompted her to be baptized in 1929 at Ebenezer, and her experiences at Greater Beulah. She discusses church activities and outreach, her presidency of the choir and favorite gospel song, the importance of Bible study and her favorite Bible verse, current and prior reverends at Beulah and Ebenezer, her faith in God and her philosophy of addressing problems directly and treating all people with respect.</abstract>
  <abstract displayLabel="Link to Abstract">http://www.lib.lsu.edu/sites/all/files/oralhistory/abstracts/mckinley/3_churches/Butler_Virginia_T1270.pdf</abstract>
  <note type="content" displayLabel="Note">This collection includes materials accessioned as Mss. 4700.0892; A digital version of the transcript (pdf) exists for duplication purposes; A digital version of the audio recording (mp3) exists for duplication purposes and public access in the Special Collections Reading Room; Interview conducted by Shawnte Green, Chastity Lovely, Melvin Heard, and Beau Bogart.</note>
  <note type="biographical/historical" displayLabel="Biographical Note">Virginia Butler was born to Ed and Patsy Butler and raised in St. Francisville, La., in the early 1900s. As a child, she worked in the fields. After moving to Baton Rouge, she had a religious experience in which she heard the voice of God. She was baptized in 1929 at Ebenezer Baptist Church and later became an active member of Greater Beulah Baptist Church, where she was president of the choir for almost forty years.</note>
